main_text: #Mozambique: STEMA to rehabilitate grain handling equipment â€“ AIMThe Matola Grain Silos and Terminal Company (STEMA) in Maputo province hopes to invest about 14 million dollars in rehabilitating its equipment so that it can increase its grain handling capacity.â€œTo achieve this goal we shall resort to the banks and to our partnersâ€ said the STEMA chairperson Arlindo Chilundo at a press conference on Monday shortly after a visit to the companyâ€™s premises by the Plan and Budget Commission (CPO) of the Mozambican parliament the Assembly of the Republic.(...)He added that STEMA still has enough space to meet the demand for grain imports from all the milling companies in southern Mozambique. â€œWeâ€™ve been working with all the importersâ€ he said. â€œSTEMA does not buy the products directly. It just manages the bulk grain unloaded from the ships which is later picked up by the buyersâ€.He warned that the price of wheat will continue to rise on the international market because of Russiaâ€™s war against Ukraine (between them the two countries used to account for about 40 per cent of all wheat exports). One shipload of wheat arrived last week and two other ships are due to arrive before the end of May.â€œChannelling this wheat to the market will depend on the flexibility of the milling companies in replenishing their stocks as quickly as possible so that the price of bread does not rise too muchâ€ he said.The wheat arriving in Mozambique this month was harvested before the Russian invasion of Ukraine but Chilundo said the price was already oscillating since the demand for wheat was outstripping the supply.The full impact of the Ukraine war would not be felt until next year. Chiludo said that because of the war which has led to the closure of Ukraineâ€™s Black Sea ports Ukraineâ€™s wheat exports will decline while international sanctions will limit how much Russia can put on the world market.(...)READ ALL:https://buff.ly/3M1nznSSource: AIM#Mocambique #Wheat #Ukraine #SADC #Africa

{"1": {"comment_id": "clubofmozambique"  "comment_text": "#Mozambique: STEMA to rehabilitate grain handling equipment â€“ AIM

The Matola Grain Silos and Terminal Company (STEMA)  in Maputo province  hopes to invest about 14 million dollars in rehabilitating its equipment so that it can increase its grain handling capacity.

â€œTo achieve this goal  we shall resort to the banks and to our partnersâ€  said the STEMA chairperson  Arlindo Chilundo  at a press conference on Monday  shortly after a visit to the companyâ€™s premises by the Plan and Budget Commission (CPO) of the Mozambican parliament  the Assembly of the Republic.

(...)
He added that STEMA still has enough space to meet the demand for grain imports from all the milling companies in southern Mozambique. â€œWeâ€™ve been working with all the importersâ€  he said. â€œSTEMA does not buy the products directly. It just manages the bulk grain unloaded from the ships  which is later picked up by the buyersâ€.

He warned that the price of wheat will continue to rise on the international market because of Russiaâ€™s war against Ukraine (between them  the two countries used to account for about 40 per cent of all wheat exports). One shipload of wheat arrived last week  and two other ships are due to arrive before the end of May.

â€œChannelling this wheat to the market will depend on the flexibility of the milling companies in replenishing their stocks as quickly as possible  so that the price of bread does not rise too muchâ€  he said.

The wheat arriving in Mozambique this month was harvested before the Russian invasion of Ukraine  but Chilundo said the price was already oscillating since the demand for wheat was outstripping the supply.

The full impact of the Ukraine war would not be felt until next year. Chiludo said that because of the war  which has led to the closure of Ukraineâ€™s Black Sea ports  Ukraineâ€™s wheat exports will decline  while international sanctions will limit how much Russia can put on the world market.

main_text: If you your partner or one of your other children has a food allergy the thought of introducing that food to your new baby can cause some anxiety.The delay of the family memberâ€™s trigger food is not recommended. There is no evidence that delay of introduction has a protective effect on food allergies.Itâ€™s important to remember to consider the food allergic person to ensure that they remain safe during the introduction of a food that they are allergic to. Prepare/serve food on separate plates and with different cutlery than the allergic person uses.Speak with your pediatrician or allergist to see if there should be an introduction plan to move forward. This may put your mind at ease when it comes to feeding a potential allergen.Donâ€™t introduce foods before 4 months of age and preferably around 6 months of age. This should include both top allergens food family members may be allergic to and other foods that your family eats. Of course DO NOT feed or reintroduce your baby any food you know that they already have an allergy to without supervision from an allergist.As always contact your pediatrician or dietitian for concerns about adjusting your childâ€™s diet.#foodallergy #cmpa #food #allergy #startingsolids #solidfood #babyfoodideas #babyfood #peanut #peanutallergy #celiacdisease #wheat #dietitian #nutrition #infantnutrition #breastfeeding #breastfeed #breastfed #foodallergymom #fpies
comment:
{"1": {"comment_id": "bloompedsnutrition"  "comment_text": "If you  your partner  or one of your other children has a food allergy  the thought of introducing that food to your new baby can cause some anxiety.

The delay of the family memberâ€™s trigger food is not recommended. There is no evidence that delay of introduction has a protective effect on food allergies.

Itâ€™s important to remember to consider the food allergic person to ensure that they remain safe during the introduction of a food that they are allergic to. Prepare/serve food on separate plates and with different cutlery than the allergic person uses.

Speak with your pediatrician or allergist to see if there should be an introduction plan to move forward. This may put your mind at ease when it comes to feeding a potential allergen.

Donâ€™t introduce foods before 4 months of age  and preferably around 6 months of age. This should include both top allergens  food family members may be allergic to  and other foods that your family eats. Of course  DO NOT feed or reintroduce your baby any food you know that they already have an allergy to without supervision from an allergist.

As always  contact your pediatrician or dietitian for concerns about adjusting your childâ€™s diet.

comment:
{"1": {"comment_id": "foodaffairby_sneha"  "comment_text": "Aatta Laadu.
This sweet is made from whole wheat flour  ghee and sugar. I have also added crushed almonds in it.
Ingredients:-
2 cups whole wheat flour
1/2 cup sugar  1/4 cup water 
2 cardamoms crushed 
Ghee- 1/2 cup + 1 tsp.
1/4 cup almonds roasted and crushed
Method:-
First dry roast the flour in a thick pan for 10-15 mins till it becomes light brown.
In the mean while make sugar bhura- make a one string syrup using sugar and water  once syrup is made  add one tsp ghee and switch off flame. The sugar then turns into crystalline form.

main_text: I had my appointment yesterday with the child psychologist.We are offered this service through my sons allergy teamitâ€™s just an appointment for me and I get to talk about how living with my sons allergies has a mental affect on me.Thereâ€™s usually a point in these appointments where I get quite emotional.Yesterday we spoke about how I find it quite upsetting when people ask me if my son will outgrow his allergies or the famous comment â€œIâ€™m sure heâ€™ll outgrow themâ€ I appreciate people ask these questions out of interest and not to be negative but I find them very hard.If I had a crystal ballI would love to say YEShe will outgrow them!I explained how always having to explain to people makes it hit home each time and a little piece of my heart breaks every time Iâ€™m asked these questions.Obviously our ultimate goal and wish is that he will outgrow them but as we donâ€™t know what the future holdsI find it a really difficult question to answer.We take each day as it comesliving with his allergies and also being realistic in that he may not outgrow his allergies or all of them.Just wondering if anybody else finds these questions hard too?...#freefromlife #allergies #allergylife #milk #egg #wheat #soya #legumes #bananas #allergycooking #allergyfriendly #allergycommunity #allergyawareness #cmpa #wheatallergy #eggallergy #soyaallergy #bananaallergy #legumeallergy #allergymum
comment:
{"1": {"comment_id": "a_mum.a_son_and_allergies_"  "comment_text": "I had my appointment yesterday with the child psychologist.We are offered this service through my sons allergy team itâ€™s just an appointment for me and I get to talk about how living with my sons allergies has a mental affect on me.

Thereâ€™s usually a point in these appointments where I get quite emotional.Yesterday we spoke about how I find it quite upsetting when people ask me if my son will outgrow his allergies or the famous comment â€œIâ€™m sure heâ€™ll outgrow themâ€ I appreciate people ask these questions out of interest and not to be negative but I find them very hard.If I had a crystal ball I would love to say YES he will outgrow them!I explained how always having to explain to people makes it hit home each time and a little piece of my heart breaks every time Iâ€™m asked these questions.

Obviously our ultimate goal and wish is that he will outgrow them but as we donâ€™t know what the future holds I find it a really difficult question to answer.We take each day as it comes living with his allergies and also being realistic in that he may not outgrow his allergies or all of them.

Just wondering if anybody else finds these questions hard too?
.
.
.

main_text: The government on Monday decided to procure an additional 4.5 million metric tonnes of wheat including three million metric tonnes from abroad and also allowed the continuation of subsidies on essential edible items to cushion low-income people against soaring inflation.The Economic Coordination Committee (ECC) of the Cabinet took the decision for more procurements after the domestic production fell short of the target by 9% due to bad weather and shortages of inputs. Federal Minister for Finance Miftah Ismail presided over the ECC meeting.For more tap the link in our bio.#etribune #news #latest #ECC #Wheat #TribuneBusiness

Ingredients:
250 g. cracked wheat
1 medium onion (grated)
2 medium carrots (diced small)
150 g. celery (chopped small)
60 g. parsley (finely chopped)
2 tsp. flour
Juice of a lemon
5 cups of water
Salt  black pepper and turmeric powder
Olive oil

Instructions:
1) Wash the cracked wheat in a large bowl and drain.
2) Heat olive oil in a pot over medium heat; sautÃ© onion until soft.
3) Add flour  salt  pepper and turmeric.
4) Add cracked wheat  celery  carrots and water. Cover and let cook.
5) After 1 hour  add parsley and let cook for 30 minutes.
6) Add lemon juice and serve the soup immediately.

main_text: The Economic Coordination Committee (ECC) of the Cabinet has approved import of three million metric tonnes of wheat and decided to continue with the former Prime Ministerâ€™s Relief Package announced in 2020 for another two months â€“ May and June 2022 â€“ to provide subsidy on five essential commodities.The ECC meeting presided over by Minister for Finance and Revenue Miftah Ismail on a summary moved by the Ministry of National Food Security and Research after discussing the current world scenario as well as its effects on the world economy and demand-supply situation of wheat in the country approved three MMT of wheat import on need basis depending upon the demand of the PASSCO and provincial governments to build up strategic reserves and to stabilize wheat prices in the country.The meeting directed the concerned authorities to frame modalities for financing and procurement.#ECC #wheat #edibleitems
comment:

The ECC meeting presided over by Minister for Finance and Revenue Miftah Ismail on a summary moved by the Ministry of National Food Security and Research after discussing the current world scenario  as well as  its effects on the world economy and demand-supply situation of wheat in the country  approved three MMT of wheat import on need basis  depending upon the demand of the PASSCO and provincial governments to build up strategic reserves and to stabilize wheat prices in the country.

The meeting directed the concerned authorities to frame modalities for financing and procurement.

Spread it slowly. (Do not press the ladle with pressure). Let the flame be low while spreading the batter. Sprinkle little oil on top of dosa.Cook on medium flameTurn the other side and cook till slightly golden brown.Take it out and serve or enjoy with your favourite side dish.Ghee or Butter is optional.If you like crispy dosa do cook completely on low flame.But it turns very hard#breakfastclub#wheat#dosalove#yummyfoodğŸ˜‹#yummyfoods#easyrecipe#healthyeats#healthyeats#indianblogger
comment:
{"1": {"comment_id": "adige_by_nalini"  "comment_text": "Breakfast Recipes.
Wheat flour + Milk Dose.Ghee smeared Dosa
Chutney Pudi.
Jaggery.

Wheat dosa is soft and Yummy.
How to Prepare:
Wheat Flour : 2 cups.
Boiled and cooled Milk : 1 Cup.
Semolina Medium/ Rava : 2 tbs.
Salt to taste
Mix all the ingredients nicely add required water.
The batter consistency is to be little thinner than normal dosa batter.
Heat a pan  clean with a kitchen tissue.
Add a ladle of batter. Spread it slowly. (Do not press the ladle with pressure). Let the flame be low while spreading the batter. Sprinkle little oil on top of dosa.
Cook on medium flame
Turn the other side and cook till slightly golden brown.
Take it out and serve or enjoy with your favourite side dish.
Ghee or Butter is optional.
If you like crispy dosa do cook completely on low flame.
But it turns very hard

main_text: A few evenings ago after taking photos of stormy skies I stopped to take a sunset photo over a wheat field south of Granger Texas. As I finished my visual wandering I met Steve a Granger-area farmer. "That's our wheat" he said. It was a quiet night giving us time to visit a few minutes. Steve mentioned recent tornados that blew through the area. His parent's home sustained damage their barn destroyed. They are okay. His father is in his 90s mother in her 80s. Photos of Steve make this post a better one. The last image shows Steve's family crops corn at left wheat on the right expressive skies overhead. Scenes from farm country on the Blackland Prairie. #wheat #farmers #blacklandprairie #inspiretexasnow #grangertexas #texasphotographer #landscape #pictorial #sunset #nikon #nikonusa

main_text: Today was an incredibly beautiful day! Every day is beautiful in its own way but I guess you could say being outside was exceptionally pleasant today. The two pictures I took are of one of our three Einkorn fields. Despite all the incredible attributes of Einkorn one of the criticisms of many cash crops wheat included (even if grown organically) is that when planted it is considered a monoculture meaning it is one species grown by itself. This may be true of conventional wheat where a pre-planting dousing with herbicides kills everything or heavy tillage for weeks is used to control young weeds. This is not the case in our Einkorn fields as you can see from the photos every gap between the Einkorn the ground is covered with dozens of different â€œweedsâ€ many of which are flowering. The Einkorn outcompetes them and rises above and eventually blocks enough light to impede their growth at least until after harvesting. When standing in the fields you can hear the bees buzzing and see insects of every kind working away. Itâ€™s anything but a monoculture!

main_text: Wheat berries are the edible part of the wheat kernel before it undergoes any processing. Since the kernels are left intact nearly all the nutrients remain. These chewy nutty and high-fiber grains can be used in many different ways. comment:
{"1": {"comment_id": "deviant_films"  "comment_text": "As I Walked Out One Evening

W. H. Auden 

As I walked out one evening 
   Walking down Bristol Street 
The crowds upon the pavement
   Were fields of harvest wheat.

And down by the brimming river
   I heard a lover sing
Under an arch of the railway:
   'Love has no ending.

'I'll love you  dear  I'll love you
   Till China and Africa meet 
And the river jumps over the mountain
   And the salmon sing in the street 

'I'll love you till the ocean
   Is folded and hung up to dry
And the seven stars go squawking
   Like geese about the sky.

'The years shall run like rabbits 
   For in my arms I hold
The Flower of the Ages 
   And the first love of the world.'

But all the clocks in the city
   Began to whirr and chime:
'O let not Time deceive you 
   You cannot conquer Time.

'In the burrows of the Nightmare
   Where Justice naked is 
Time watches from the shadow
   And coughs when you would kiss.

'In headaches and in worry
   Vaguely life leaks away 
And Time will have his fancy
   To-morrow or to-day.

'Into many a green valley
   Drifts the appalling snow;
Time breaks the threaded dances
   And the diver's brilliant bow.

'O plunge your hands in water 
   Plunge them in up to the wrist;
Stare  stare in the basin
   And wonder what you've missed.

'The glacier knocks in the cupboard 
   The desert sighs in the bed 
And the crack in the tea-cup opens
   A lane to the land of the dead.

'Where the beggars raffle the banknotes
   And the Giant is enchanting to Jack 
And the Lily-white Boy is a Roarer 
   And Jill goes down on her back.

'O look  look in the mirror 
   O look in your distress:
Life remains a blessing
   Although you cannot bless.

'O stand  stand at the window
   As the tears scald and start;
You shall love your crooked neighbour
   With your crooked heart.'

It was late  late in the evening 
   The lovers they were gone;
The clocks had ceased their chiming 
   And the deep river ran on.

#auden #rollingstones #thefieldsareripe #england #jackandjill #isherwood #fleurdemal #baudelaire #wheat #harvest"}}

main_text: What is a Wheat Allergy?A Wheat allergy is an allergic reaction to foods containing wheat.â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €Did you know...- Wheat allergy is most common in babies and toddlers. It is reported that approximately 65% will grow out of their allergy by the age of 12 years.â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €- Although a wheat allergy is rare in adults it is a food that will most commonly trigger a severe anaphylactic reaction.â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €Wheat allergy symptoms can occur within minutes or sometimes hours of being ingested. Some allergic symptoms such as abdominal pain nausea and vomiting can also be found in coeliac disease symptoms an autoimmune disease which can make those affected by it extremely unwell. It is important to see an allergy professional for an accurate diagnosis.â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €How to manage a Wheat Allergy?- Strict avoidance is critical of both wheat in foods and non-food products. Wheat can be found in surprising places such as children's play dough so it's important to check all labels.â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €- Cosmetics Regulations state that all cosmetic products sold in the UK must display a complete list of ingredients. However you may find other names used for wheat confusing such as titicum vulgare or triticum aestivum.â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €#wheat #wheatallergy #allergies #adultallergy #allergicreactions #intolerance #foodallergyfamily #foodsensitivities #anaphylaxisawareness #foodallergy #bloodtest #food #symptoms #health #lifestyle
comment:
{"1": {"comment_id": "lonmedlab"  "comment_text": "What is a Wheat Allergy?

A Wheat allergy is an allergic reaction to foods containing wheat.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
Did you know...
- Wheat allergy is most common in babies and toddlers. It is reported that approximately 65% will grow out of their allergy by the age of 12 years.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
- Although a wheat allergy is rare in adults  it is a food that will most commonly trigger a severe anaphylactic reaction.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
Wheat allergy symptoms can occur within minutes or sometimes hours of being ingested. Some allergic symptoms such as abdominal pain  nausea and vomiting can also be found in coeliac disease symptoms  an autoimmune disease which can make those affected by it extremely unwell. It is important to see an allergy professional for an accurate diagnosis.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
How to manage a Wheat Allergy?
- Strict avoidance is critical of both wheat in foods and non-food products. Wheat can be found in surprising places such as children's play dough so it's important to check all labels.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
- Cosmetics Regulations state that all cosmetic products sold in the UK  must display a complete list of ingredients. However  you may find other names used for wheat confusing  such as titicum vulgare or triticum aestivum.

Sesame has increased as an allergic food significantly worldwide over the last two decades. There is a current push to add sesame to the list of â€œ major food allergensâ€Many times I hear from clients â€œ I think it is something that I ateâ€. {"1": {"comment_id": "lorrizenoni"  "comment_text": "Food Allergy Awareness Week

This week we bring awareness to the foods that may trigger an allergic reaction.

While almost any food can trigger an allergic reaction  there are 9 foods that cause the majority of reactions.

Here  I have listed the top 6 that I have seen over the last 5 years of food testing.

The other 3 include more specific categories such as all fish  not just shellfish  separated tree nuts from peanuts and sesame. Sesame has increased as an allergic food significantly worldwide over the last two decades. There is a current push to add sesame to the list of â€œ major food allergensâ€

Many times I hear from clients  â€œ I think it is something that I ateâ€. You are the expert of your own body and when you have that intuition  it is most likely correct.

That is where I can help and actually test your blood to see if you lack the digestive enzymes to process these foods.

Which of these foods do you notice an adverse reaction?
